= CSR-01: Workload Measurement Methods and Validity in Aviation
:artifact_type: CSR
:path_name: Concept-to-Compliance
:revnumber: 1.0

== PURPOSE

Systematically review empirical methods used to measure pilot workload in aviation and evaluate their validity, reliability, sensitivity, and suitability for certification evidence.

SECTION 1 — IDENTIFYING WORKLOAD MEASUREMENT STUDIES

=== Semantic Queries

What methods are used to measure pilot workload in aviation?

How is workload measured in high-performance or tactical flight environments?

What validation studies exist for workload measurement tools in aviation?

How sensitive are workload measures to task difficulty changes?

What are limitations of subjective workload measures in aviation?

=== Keyword Searches

"pilot workload measurement"

"NASA-TLX" AND aviation

"subjective workload" AND cockpit

"objective workload metrics" AND flight

"dual-task paradigm" AND aviation

"physiological workload" AND pilot

SECTION 2 — EXTRACTION COLUMNS

=== Measurement Method

Subjective (NASA-TLX, Bedford, SWAT, etc.)

Performance-based (dual-task, error rate, RT)

Physiological (HRV, EEG, pupil dilation)

Behavioral (scan entropy, eye tracking)

Composite metric (Y/N)

=== Validity & Reliability

Construct validity discussed (Y/N)

Criterion validity tested (Y/N)

Sensitivity to task manipulation (Y/N)

Reliability reported (Y/N)

Effect size reported (Y/N)

=== Context Variables

Flight simulation / live flight

Tactical scenario (Y/N)

High tempo (Y/N)

Multi-task environment (Y/N)

Physical stressors (G, vibration) (Y/N)

=== Outcome Sensitivity

Detects overload threshold (Y/N)

Detects underload (Y/N)

Differentiates expertise levels (Y/N)

SECTION 3 — VALIDITY AND LIMITATIONS

=== Semantic Queries

When do subjective workload measures fail?

What physiological measures correlate best with performance?

Are workload measures predictive of performance degradation?

What measurement artifacts exist in flight simulation studies?

=== Keyword Searches

"workload validity" AND aviation

"physiological correlates" AND pilot workload

"predictive validity" AND workload

"measurement artifact" AND simulation

STOP CONDITION

≥ 40 empirical workload measurement studies

≥ 15 compare subjective vs objective methods

≥ 10 test validity explicitly

≥ 10 include tactical/high-tempo scenarios

